basicPropertyValues.val: Molsim is an interoperable domain ontology designed to semantically represent platform-agnostic molecular simulations as FAIR (Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable) datasets. This ontology aims to standardize the representation of molecular simulation data, processes, and methodologies across different platforms and tools.

definition.val: An organonitrogen compound of general structure RCH=N-N=CHR or RR'C=N-N=CRR'.

An atom of an element that exhibits properties that are between those of metals and nonmetals, or that has a mixture of them. The term generally includes boron, silicon, germanium, arsenic, antimony, and tellurium, while carbon, aluminium, selenium, polonium, and astatine are less commonly included.
Any main group molecular entity that is gaseous at standard temperature and pressure (STP; 0degreeC and 100 kPa).
A ketone containing a hydroxy group on the alpha-carbon relative to the C=O group.
The simplest hydroxylamine, consisting of ammonia bearing a hydroxy substituent. It is an intermediate in the biological nitrification by microbes like bacteria.
An aminopyrimidine that is pyrimidin-2-one having the amino group located at position 4.
A carbonyl group with two C-bound amine groups. The commercially available fertilizer has an analysis of 46-0-0 (N-P2O5-K2O).
A 2-aminopurine carrying a 6-oxo substituent.
A nitrile that is hydrogen cyanide in which the hydrogen has been replaced by an amino group.
The parent compound of the 6-aminopurines, composed of a purine having an amino group at C-6.
A mineral that is an inorganic nutrient which must be ingested and absorbed in adequate amounts to satisfy a wide range of essential metabolic and/or structural functions in the human body.
A compound in which a carbonyl group is bonded to two carbon atoms: R2C=O (neither R may be H).
A compound RC(=O)H, in which a carbonyl group is bonded to one hydrogen atom and to one R group.

A common and naturally occurring pyrimidine nucleobase in which the pyrimidine ring is substituted with two oxo groups at positions 2 and 4. Found in RNA, it base pairs with adenine and replaces thymine during DNA transcription.
A nitrogen oxoanion formed by loss of a proton from nitric acid. Principal species present at pH 7.3.
A compound containing at least one carbon-halogen bond (where X is a halogen atom).
A pyrimidine nucleobase that is uracil in which the hydrogen at position 5 is replaced by a methyl group.
A pseudohalide anion obtained by deprotonation of the thiol group of thiocyanic acid.

A member of the class of condensed ureas that is the compound formed by the condensation of two molecules of urea; the parent compound of the biuret group of compounds. Used as a non-protein nitrogen source in ruminant feed.
An iron group element atom that has atomic number 26.
That part of DNA or RNA that may be involved in pairing.
An acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbon having the general formula CnH2n+2, and therefore consisting entirely of hydrogen atoms and saturated carbon atoms.

A compound having the structure RC#N; thus a C-substituted derivative of hydrocyanic acid, HC#N. In systematic nomenclature, the suffix nitrile denotes the triply bound #N atom, not the carbon atom attached to it.
A calcium salt that lacks C-H bonds
A potassium salt that lacks C-H bonds
A carbon group element atom with a symbol Fl and atomic number 114.
A boron group element atom with a symbol Nh and atomic number 113.
A pnictogen atom with a symbol Mc and atomic number 115.
A chalcogen atom with a symbol Lv and atomic number 116.
A halogen atom with a symbol Ts and atomic number 117.
A p-block element atom with a symbol Og and atomic number 118.
Any aminopurine having the amino substituent at the 2-position.
Any compound having 6-aminopurine (adenine) as part of its structure.
An organosulfur compound having the structure R2S=O or R2C=S=O (R =/= H).

An organic group formed by removing one or more hydroxy groups from an oxoacid that has the general structure RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l =/= 0). Although the term is almost always applied to organic compounds, with carboxylic acid as the oxoacid, acyl groups can in principle be derived from other types of acids such as sulfonic acids or phosphonic acids.
A univalent group -CnH2n+1 derived from an alkane by removal of a hydrogen atom from any carbon atom.
Acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having a carbon-carbon triple bond and the general formula CnH2n-2, RC#CR.
A hydroxynitrile in which the hydroxy group is located on the carbon alpha to the carbonitrile group.
Any purine having at least one amino substituent.
A monoatomic or polyatomic species having one or more elementary charges of the electron.
Any nitrogen molecular entity containing the group -N3.
Organooxygen compounds that are salts or esters of carbonic acid, H2CO3.
A halogen molecular entity containing one or more atoms of chlorine.
A group of metal atoms that are located in the periodic table between transition metals and metalloids.
Any constitutionally or isotopically distinct atom, molecule, ion, ion pair, radical, radical ion, complex, conformer etc., identifiable as a separately distinguishable entity.
Salts and esters of cyanic acid, HOC#N; compounds carrying the cyanate functional group -O-C#N.
Salts and C-organyl derivatives of hydrogen cyanide, HC#N.
An alpha-hydroxynitrile resulting from the formal addition of hydrogen cyanide to the C=O bond of an aldehyde or ketone.
A compound that contains two hydroxy groups, generally assumed to be, but not necessarily, alcoholic. Aliphatic diols are also called glycols.
A chemical entity is a physical entity of interest in chemistry including molecular entities, parts thereof, and chemical substances.
A defined linked collection of atoms or a single atom within a molecular entity.
A cyclic compound having as ring members atoms of carbon and at least of one other element.
A compound consisting of carbon and hydrogen only.

A compound, RkE(=O)lNHOH, derived from an oxoacid RkE(=O)l(OH) (l =/= 0) by replacing -OH with -NHOH, and derivatives thereof. Specific examples of hydroxamic acids are preferably named as N-hydroxy amides.
Hydroxides are chemical compounds containing a hydroxy group or salts containing hydroxide (OH(-)).

An alpha-hydroxy ketone in which the carbonyl group and the hydroxy group are linked by a carbon bearing one hydrogen and one organyl group. Secondary alpha-hydroxy ketones are also known as acyloins, and are formally derived from reductive coupling of two carboxylic acid groups.
Hydroxylamine, H2N-OH, and its hydrocarbyl derivatives.
Any nitrile compound which also contains a hydroxy group.

Compounds having the structure RN=CR2 (R = H, hydrocarbyl). Thus analogues of aldehydes or ketones, having NR doubly bonded to carbon; aldimines have the structure RCH=NR, ketimines have the structure R'2C=NR (where R' is not H). Imines include azomethines and Schiff bases. Imine is used as a suffix in systematic nomenclature to denote the C=NH group excluding the carbon atom.
A compound which contains oxygen, at least one other element, and at least one hydrogen bound to oxygen, and which produces a conjugate base by loss of positive hydrogen ion(s) (hydrons).
A molecular entity that contains no carbon.
Chemical element with atomic number 53.
A salt is an assembly of cations and anions.
A molecular entity having a net electric charge.
Cyclic amides of amino carboxylic acids, having a 1-azacycloalkan-2-one structure, or analogues having unsaturation or heteroatoms replacing one or more carbon atoms of the ring.
Any cyclic carboxylic ester containing a 1-oxacycloalkan-2-one structure, or an analogue having unsaturation or heteroatoms replacing one or more carbon atoms of the ring.
Any polyatomic entity that is an electrically neutral entity consisting of more than one atom.
Any organic ion with a net negative charge.
An organooxygen compound with formula ROR, where R is not hydrogen.
A compound having bonds between one or more metal atoms and one or more carbon atoms of an organyl group.
An organosilicon compound is a compound containing at least one carbon-silicon bond.
An oxide is a chemical compound of oxygen with other chemical elements.
Compounds of structure R2C=NOH derived from condensation of aldehydes or ketones with hydroxylamine. Oximes from aldehydes may be called aldoximes; those from ketones may be called ketoximes.

Salts and esters of phosphoric and oligophosphoric acids and their chalcogen analogues. In inorganic chemistry, the term is also used to describe anionic coordination entities with phosphorus as central atom.
A compound that contains two or more hydroxy groups.
Any alkali metal salt having potassium(1+) as the cation.

Derivatives of oxoacids RnE(=O)OH in which the hydroxy group is replaced by an amino group and the oxo group is replaced by =NR. In organic chemistry an unspecified amidine is commonly a carboxamidine.
A nucleobase whose skeleton is derived from purine.
A class of imidazopyrimidines that consists of purine and its substituted derivatives.
A nucleobase whose skeleton is derived from pyrimidine.
A nitrogen molecular entity that is electronically neutral but which contains a quaternary nitrogen.
A molecular entity possessing an unpaired electron.

Molecules or ions formed by the incomplete one-electron reduction of oxygen. They contribute to the microbicidal activity of phagocytes, regulation of signal transduction and gene expression, and the oxidative damage to biopolymers.
An inorganic chloride salt having sodium(1+) as the counterion.
Any alkali metal salt having sodium(1+) as the cation.
Any sulfur molecular entity that involves either covalently bonded or anionic sulfur.
Any sulfurous acid derivative that is a salt or an ester of sulfurous acid.
An ester in which one or both oxygens of an ester group have been replaced by divalent sulfur.
An element whose atom has an incomplete d sub-shell, or which can give rise to cations with an incomplete d sub-shell.
A chemical compound containing three hydroxy groups.
A univalent carboacyl group is a group formed by loss of OH from the carboxy group of a carboxylic acid.
A neutral compound having formal unit electrical charges of opposite sign on non-adjacent atoms. Sometimes referred to as inner salts, dipolar ions (a misnomer).
A cobalt group element atom that has atomic number 27.
A chromium group element atom that has atomic number 24.
Chemical element (nickel group element atom) with atomic number 28.
A monocarboxylic acid amide that is urea where one of the amino groups has been replaced with hydrazine.
The conjugate base formed when the carboxy group of a carboxylic acid is deprotonated.
A phosphorus oxoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from the hydroxy group of phosphinic acid.
An organosulfur compound in which a thiol group, -SH, is attached to a carbon atom of any aliphatic or aromatic moiety.
A carboxamide derived from a monocarboxylic acid.
A phosphorus hydride consisting of a single pentavalent phosphorus carrying five hydrogens. The parent hydride of the phosphorane class.
A metallic element first identified and named from the brilliant indigo (Latin indicum) blue line in its flame spectrum.
A metallic element first identified and named from the brilliant green line in its flame spectrum (from Greek thetaalphalambdalambdaomicronsigma, a green shoot).
Alkaline earth metal atom with atomic number 4.
A compound in which a hydroxy group, -OH, is attached to a saturated carbon atom.
A metal chloride salt with a K(+) counterion.
An alkyl group that is the univalent group derived from methane by removal of a hydrogen atom.

An acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbon having one carbon-carbon double bond and the general formula CnH2n. Acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having more than one double bond are alkadienes, alkatrienes, etc.
A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups.
Any cyclic ether in which the oxygen atom forms part of a 3-membered ring.
An amide is a derivative of an oxoacid RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l =/= 0) in which an acidic hydroxy group has been replaced by an amino or substituted amino group.

An organic fundamental parent is a structure used as a basis for substitutive names in organic nomenclature, containing, in addition to one or more hydrogen atoms, a single atom of an element, a number of atoms (alike or different) linked together to form an unbranched chain, a monocyclic or polycyclic ring system, or a ring assembly or ring/chain system.
Any substituent group which does not contain carbon.
Any substituent group or skeleton containing carbon.
A univalent group formed by removing a hydrogen atom from a hydrocarbon.
Any organic substituent group, regardless of functional type, having one free valence at a carbon atom.
A chemical entity constituting the smallest component of an element having the chemical properties of the element.
A derivative of an oxoacid RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l =/= 0) in which an acidic hydroxy group has been replaced by an amino or substituted amino group.
A molecular entity all atoms of which have the same atomic number.
An organosulfur compound is a compound containing at least one carbon-sulfur bond.
Imines derived from aldehydes, i.e. compounds having the structure RCH=NR.
An anion consisting of more than one atom.
A heteroorganic entity is an organic molecular entity in which carbon atoms or organic groups are bonded directly to one or more heteroatoms.
A molecular entity containing one or more atoms of an alkali metal.
An alkaline earth molecular entity is a molecular entity containing one or more atoms of an alkaline earth metal.
Any p-block element atom that is in group 15 of the periodic table: nitrogen, phosphorus, arsenic, antimony and bismuth.
A p-block molecular entity containing any pnictogen.
Any p-block element belonging to the group 16 family of the periodic table.
Any p-block molecular entity containing a chalcogen.
An ester of a carboxylic acid, R(1)C(=O)OR(2), where R(1) = H or organyl and R(2) = organyl.
A radioactive metallic element discovered in 1898 by Marie Sklodowska Curie and named after her home country, Poland (Latin Polonia).
An atom belonging to one of the main groups (found in the s- and p- blocks) of the periodic table.
A cobalt group element atom of atomic number 45.
Chemical element (nickel group element atom) with atomic number 46.
A copper group element atom with atomic number 111. The the ninth member of the 6d series of transition metals, it is an extremely radioactive, synthetic element. Average mass is around 281.

A zinc group element atom with a symbol Cn and atomic number 112. All its isotopes are intensely radioactive. Prior to its discovery, it had the placeholder name ununbium (in accordance with IUPAC recommendations). Following its discovery (in Darmstadt, 1996) and subsequent confirmation, the name copernicium was adopted in 2010.
An atom of an element that exhibits typical metallic properties, being typically shiny, with high electrical and thermal conductivity.
The sulfur oxoanion formed by deprotonation of sulfonic acid.
Any main group element atom belonging to the p-block of the periodic table.

A carbon oxoacid acid carrying at least one -C(=O)OH group and having the structure RC(=O)OH, where R is any any monovalent functional group. Carboxylic acids are the most common type of organic acid.
A molecular entity containing one or more atoms from any of groups 1, 2, 13, 14, 15, 16, 17, and 18 of the periodic table.
Any molecule that consists of a series of atoms joined together to form a ring.
A molecule that features two fused rings.

Acyclic and cyclic hydrocarbons having one or more carbon-carbon double bonds, apart from the formal ones in aromatic compounds. The class olefins subsumes alkenes and cycloalkenes and the corresponding polyenes.
Acyclic (branched or unbranched) and cyclic (with or without side chain) hydrocarbons having one or more carbon-carbon triple bonds.
Acyclic branched or unbranched hydrocarbons having one or more carbon-carbon double bond.
Acyclic (branched or unbranched) hydrocarbons having one or more carbon-carbon triple bonds.
Any acyclic or cyclic, saturated or unsaturated carbon compound, excluding aromatic compounds.

A cyclically conjugated molecular entity with a stability (due to delocalization) significantly greater than that of a hypothetical localized structure (e.g. Kekule structure) is said to possess aromatic character.
A polycyclic compound in which at least one of the rings contains at least one non-carbon atom.
A bicyclic compound in which at least one of the rings contains at least one skeletal heteroatom.
An s-block molecular entity is a molecular entity containing one or more atoms of an s-block element.
A main group molecular entity that contains one or more atoms of a p-block element.
Hydrides are chemical compounds of hydrogen with other chemical elements.
When two or more amino acids combine to form a peptide, the elements of water are removed, and what remains of each amino acid is called an amino-acid residue.
An amino-acid residue derived from an alpha-amino acid.
An organic compound having at least one hydroxy group attached to a carbon atom.
Alkenols; the term refers specifically to vinylic alcohols, which have the structure HOCR'=CR2. Enols are tautomeric with aldehydes (R' = H) or ketones (R' =/= H).
Any organic molecule that consists of atoms connected in the form of a ring.

A heterocyclic compound formally derived from an arene by replacement of one or more methine (-C=) and/or vinylene (-CH=CH-) groups by trivalent or divalent heteroatoms, respectively, in such a way as to maintain the continuous pi-electron system characteristic of aromatic systems and a number of out-of-plane pi-electrons corresponding to the Hueckel rule (4n+2).
Organic aromatic compounds having one or more hydroxy groups attached to a benzene or other arene ring.
An amino compound in which the amino group is linked directly to an aromatic system.
Salts in which the cation has the structure R2C=N(+)R2. Thus N-hydronated imines and their N-substituted derivatives.
Neutral molecules having charge-separated forms with an onium atom which bears no hydrogen atoms and that is not adjacent to the anionic atom.
Derivatives of nitriles having the general structure R-C#N(+)-Y(-). A subclass of 1,3-dipolar compounds including nitrile imides, nitrile oxides, nitrile sulfides and nitrile ylides.
Any heteroorganic entity containing at least one carbon-nitrogen bond.
An amide of a sulfonic acid RS(=O)2NR'2.
Compounds derived from oxoacids RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l =/= 0) by replacing -OH  by -NRNR2 (R groups are commonly H). (IUPAC).
A hydrazide consisting of hydrazine carrying one or more carboacyl groups.
An oxoanion is an anion derived from an oxoacid by loss of hydron(s) bound to oxygen.
Compounds having two amino groups bonded to the same carbon, R2C(NR2)2.
A secondary alcohol is a compound in which a hydroxy group, -OH, is attached to a saturated carbon atom which has two other carbon atoms attached to it.

A compound formally derived from an oxoacid RkE(=O)l(OH)m (l > 0) and an alcohol, phenol, heteroarenol, or enol by linking with formal loss of water from an acidic hydroxy group of the former and a hydroxy group of the latter.

A compound having a nitro group, -NO2 (free valence on nitrogen), which may be attached to carbon, nitrogen (as in nitramines), or oxygen (as in nitrates), among other elements (in the absence of specification, C-nitro compounds are usually implied).
Compounds having the nitroso group, -NO, attached to carbon, or to another element, most commonly nitrogen or oxygen.

N-Nitroso amines, compounds of the structure R2NNO. Compounds RNHNO are not ordinarily isolable, but they, too, are nitrosamines. The name is a contraction of N-nitrosoamine and, as such, does not require the N locant.

Phosphane (PH3) and compounds derived from it by substituting one, two or three hydrogen atoms by hydrocarbyl groups: RPH2, R2PH, R3P (R =/= H) are called primary, secondary and tertiary phosphines, respectively. A specific phosphine is preferably named as a substituted phosphane.
lambda(5)-phosphane and its hydrocarbyl derivatives. By extension the term also applies to phosphonium ylides.
Any molecular entity consisting of more than one atom.
An ion consisting of more than one atom.
A thiocarbonyl compound in which the carbon of the thiocarbonyl group is bonded to two other carbon atoms, R2C=S (neither R may be H).
Any compound containing the carbonyl group, C=O. The term is commonly used in the restricted sense of aldehydes and ketones, although it actually includes carboxylic acids and derivatives.
Organic compounds containing an oxygen atom, =O, doubly bonded to carbon or another element.
Organic compounds having an oxygen atom formally doubly bonded to a heteroatom.
Compounds consisting of two acyl groups bonded to the same oxygen atom acyl-O-acyl.
An organochlorine compound is a compound containing at least one carbon-chlorine bond.
A compound consisting of an acyl group bonded to chlorine.
Esters of cyanic acid, HOC#N.
The simplest member of the thiourea class, consisting of urea with the oxygen atom substituted by sulfur.
An organochalcogen compound is a compound containing at least one carbon-chalcogen bond.
An organochalcogen compound containing at least one carbon-oxygen bond.
Any ether in which the oxygen atom forms part of a ring.
A molecular entity consisting of two or more chemical elements.
Any heteroatomic molecular entity that is a chemical compound of halogen with other chemical elements.
A compound consisting of an acyl group bonded to halogen.
Any olefinic compound having two double bonds from one carbon atom to two others.
Hydrocarbons (and by extension, derivatives formed by substitution) having three or more cumulative double bonds, e.g. R2C=C=C=CR2.
An amide of a carboxylic acid, having the structure RC(=O)NR2. The term is used as a suffix in systematic name formation to denote the -C(=O)NH2 group including its carbon atom.
A carboacyl group is a group formed by loss of at least one OH from the carboxy group of a carboxylic acid.
An intramolecular cyclic ester of a hydroxy sulfonic acid, analogous to lactone.
Any organonitrogen compound containing a cyclic component with nitrogen and at least one other element as ring member atoms.
Any organic heterocyclic compound containing at least one ring oxygen atom.
Cyclic hemiacetals formed by intramolecular addition of a hydroxy group to an aldehydic or ketonic carbonyl group. They are thus 1-oxacycloalkan-2-ols or unsaturated analogues.
The simplest boronic acid, consisting of borane with two of the hydrogens substituted by hydroxy groups.
Compounds having the structure RB(OH)2.
Any organic heterocyclic compound containing a benzene ring in which two of the C-H fragments have been replaced by isolobal nitrogens (the diazine parent structure).
A pyrimidine carrying one or more oxo substituents.
A member of the class of  pyrimidines that is pyrimidine substituted by at least one amino group and its derivatives.
Compounds having the structure R2C=NNR2, formally derived from aldehydes or ketones by replacing =O by =NNH2 (or substituted analogues).
A compound having the nitro group (-NO2) attached to a nitrogen atom.
Any sulfur oxoacid derivative derived from sulfurous acid.

An N-nitro compound that is guanidine in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by a nitro group. It can exist in distinct tautomeric forms, as 1-nitroguanidine (a nitroimine) or 2-nitroguanidine (a nitroamine); in both solid and in solution, the nitroimine form predominates.
Any compound having a pyrimidine as part of its structure.

A group, formally derived from acetic acid by dehydroxylation, which is fundamental to the biochemistry of all forms of life. When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.

In general, a mineral is a chemical substance that is normally crystalline formed and has been formed as a result of geological processes. The term also includes metamict substances (naturally occurring, formerly crystalline substances whose crystallinity has been destroyed by ionising radiation) and can include naturally occurring amorphous substances that have never been crystalline ('mineraloids') such as georgite and calciouranoite as well as substances formed by the action of geological processes on bigenic compounds ('biogenic minerals').
Any carbonate that is carbonic acid in which the hydrogens have been replaced by organyl groups.
A 1,3-dipolar compound having the structure: RC#N(+)-C(-)R2 <-> RC(-)=N(+)=CR2 <-> RC(+)=NC(-)R2 <-> R(.)C(.)-N=CR2.
Ethers ROR' where R has a double bond adjacent to the oxygen of the ether linkage.
Enol ethers ROR' where R' has the structure SiR''R'''R''''.
Ethers ROR' where R' has the structure SiR''R'''R''''.
An amine RNR'R'' where R has a double bond adjacent to the amine nitrogen.
Carbonyl compounds where the C=O bond is conjugated to an alkylidene group.
Imines where the C=N bond is conjugated to an alkylidene group.

A metallic element predicted as eka-aluminium by Mendeleev in 1870 and discovered by Paul-Emile Lecoq de Boisbaudran in 1875. Named in honour of France (Latin Gallia) and perhaps also from the Latin gallus cock, a translation of Lecoq.
A compound formally derived from ammonia by replacing one, two or three hydrogen atoms by organyl groups.
An imine bearing a hydrocarbyl group on the nitrogen atom R2C=NR' (R' =/= H).
Mononuclear cations derived by addition of a hydron to a mononuclear parent hydride of the pnictogen, chalcogen and halogen families.
A univalent organyl group obtained by cleaving the bond from C-2 to the side chain of a proteinogenic amino-acid.
Any compound containing the thiocarbonyl group, C=S.
Any molecular entity that contains carbon.
Any member of the class of nitrates resulting from the esterification of nitric acid with an alcohol.
Groups containing a sulfur atom doubly-bonded to two oxygen atoms.
A compound in which an anionic site Y(-) is attached directly to a heteroatom X(+) (usually nitrogen, phosphorus or sulfur) carrying a formal positive charge.

An  organic molecule that is electrically neutral carrying a positive and a negative charge in one of its major canonical descriptions. In most dipolar compounds the charges are delocalized; however the term is also applied to species where this is not the case.
A compound where a formally positive nitrogen atom is bound to a formally negative atom (carbon or other atom).
Compounds of general formula RR'NC(=S)NR''R'''.
A compound of general formula RC(=O)SR'. Compare with thionoester, RC(=S)OR'.

The electrically neutral species H2C(2.) and its derivatives, in which the carbon is covalently bonded to two univalent groups of any kind or a divalent group and bears two nonbonding electrons, which may be spin-paired (singlet state) or spin-non-paired (triplet state).
Any organic substituent group, regardless of functional type, having two free valences at carbon atom(s).
An alpha,beta-unsaturated ketone of general formula R(1)R(2)C=CR(3)-C(=O)R(4) (R(4) =/= H) in which the C=O function is conjugated to a C=C double bond at the alpha,beta position.

A ketone of general formula R(1)R(2)C=CR(3)-C(=O)R(4) (R(4) =/= H) or R(1)C#C-C(=O)R(2) (R(2) =/= H) in which the ketonic C=O function is conjugated to an unsaturated C-C bond at the alpha,beta position.
A ketone containing a halo group.
An acid in which an acidic -OH  group has been replaced by an -OOH  group.
Any organic entity containing a conjugated system of two carbon-carbon triple bonds separated by a carbon-carbon double bond (i.e. a 3-ene-1,5-diyne system).
A compound having the general formula RR'C(OH)OR'' (R'' =/= H).
A cyclic compound having as ring members atoms of at least two different elements.
Phosphine oxides are organophosphorus compounds with the formula OPR3, where R = alkyl or aryl. They are considered to be the most stable organophosphorus compounds.
An organooxygen compound having the structure RR'C(OR'')(OR''') (R'', R''' =/= H). Mixed acetals have R'' and R''' groups which differ.

The sulfur analogue of 'acetal'.  The term includes monothioacetals having the structure R2C(OR')(SR') (subclass monothioketals, R =/= H); and dithioacetals having the structure R2C(SR')2 (subclass dithioketals, R =/= H, R' =/= H).
An  acetylenic and an olefinic  compound containing a carbon chain that contains a carbon-carbon double bond and a carbon-carbon triple bond.
A chemical substance is a portion of matter of constant composition, composed of molecular entities of the same type or of different types.
A cyclic thioester of a mercapto carboxylic acid, containing a 1-thiacycloalkan-2-one structure, or an analogue having unsaturation or heteroatoms replacing one or more carbon atoms of the ring.
An inorganic radical in which a free electron resides on one or more oxygen atoms of an oxygen species.
A carbohydrazide obtained by formal condensation between hydrazinecarboxylic acid and hydrazine.

A family of nitrogen molecular entities which are highly reactive and derived from nitric oxide (.NO) and superoxide (O2.(-)) produced via the enzymatic activity of inducible nitric oxide synthase 2 (NOS2) and NADPH oxidase respectively.
An organic molecular entity containing a single carbon atom (C1).
Any organic molecular entity that is acidic and contains carbon in covalent linkage.
Any organooxygen compound that has the general formula RC(OR(1))(OR(2))(OR(3)), where R(1), R(2), R(3) =/= H.
Any molecule that consists of at least one carbon atom as part of the electrically neutral entity.

Any organic amino compound that has an amino group and a hydroxy group attached to the same carbon atom. Hemiaminals are intermediates in the formation of imines by addition of an amine to an aldehyde or ketone; those derived from primary amines are particularly unstable.
Any organic molecule containing a C#C bond.

A compound arising by replacement of one or both hydrogen atoms of acetylene (ethyne) by a metal or other cationic group. By extension, the class of acetylides includes analogous compounds derived from terminal acetylenic compound, RC#CH.
A nitrogen ylide obtained by oxygenation of any imine.
Any organic molecular entity that contains at least one C=C bond.
Any inorganic anion with a valency of one.
A hydrazone resulting from the formal condensation of an aldehyde or ketone with the non-acylated nitrogen of semicarbazide or its substituted derivatives.
Any metal which causes the onset of an allergic reaction.
In molecular simulation, a process is a sequence of computational steps to model molecular behavior. It typically includes system preparation, simulation execution, and data analysis.
Specialized computer programs used to perform molecular simulations and analyze results. These include molecular dynamics engines, visualization tools, and data analysis packages, and others.

The initial setup phase of a molecular simulation, involving system construction and parameter assignment. This includes building molecular structures, defining force fields, and setting initial conditions.
The actual running of a molecular simulation on a computer or cluster. It involves solving equations of motion for atoms over time, often for nanoseconds to microseconds of simulated time.

The examination and interpretation of data produced by molecular simulations. This includes calculating various properties, visualizing trajectories, and extracting meaningful insights from the simulation results.
The process of adding or removing protons (hydrogens) to atoms or molecules in a simulation system. It's crucial for accurately representing the chemical state of molecules at a given pH.
A computational representation of a molecular system used in simulations. It includes the molecular structure, force field parameters, and environmental conditions.
A force field is a mathematical expression describing the dependence of the energy of a system on. the coordinates of its particles.
Lipid force field is the force field being used to model lipid molecules in simulations.
Protein force field is the force field being used to model proteins in simulations.

A specialized parameter set optimized for deoxyribonucleic acid simulations, designed to accurately represent the structural properties of DNA double helices, non-canonical structures, and DNA-protein complexes. (UNVERIFIED)
RNA force field is the force field being used to model RNAs in simulations

A specialized force field designed for modeling mono- and polysaccharides, with parameters optimized to reproduce the complex conformational preferences and hydrogen bonding patterns of sugar molecules. (UNVERIFIED)
A category encompassing force fields designed for organic compounds beyond the standard biomolecular classes, including drug-like molecules, cofactors, and synthetic polymers. (UNVERIFIED)
Water model force field is the force field being used to model water in simulations
A specialized parameter set for modeling atomic and molecular ions in solution, optimized to reproduce hydration free energies and ion-water structural properties. (UNVERIFIED)

Other organic molecule force field is the force field being used to model ligands in simulations / The set of parameters and equations used to model the interactions and behavior of small molecules (ligands) that bind to proteins or other biomolecules.

The simplest type of basis set that uses the minimum number of functions needed to represent all the electrons of each atom, providing qualitative but often inaccurate results due to their limited flexibility. (UNVERIFIED)
Lipid21 is a lipid force filed type available under AMBER software package (2022).
Lipid14 is a lipid force filed type available under AMBER software package (2014).
Lipid17 is a lipid force filed type available under AMBER software package (2017).
ff14SB is a protein force-field type, compatible with TIP3P water model.
TIP3P is a water force-field type. It specifies a 3-site rigid water molecule with charges and Lennard-Jones parameters assigned to each of the 3 atoms.
General AMBER force field (gaff) is a Small Organic Molecule Force Field designed for small organic molecules, compatible with AMBER protein force fields.
General AMBER force field 2 (gaff2) is a Small Organic Molecule Force Field designed for small organic molecules, compatible with AMBER protein force fields.

The substance or molecular system being studied in a simulation, which can include salt, proteins, nucleic acids, small molecules, lipids, or their combinations. Materials in molecular simulations are represented by atomic coordinates and parameters that define their behavior.
Water type is the specific water model type used to represent water molecules, designed to mimic the behavior of real water in simulations.
Optimal Point Charges Model (OPM) is a water type model  designed without geometrical restraints. Considerably better reproduces the six bulk properties of water.
Box type is  the 3D-shape of simulation space used to contain the molecular system.
Rhombic dodecahedron uses a 12-sided, space-filling shape. Considered to be more efficient than a cube.
Truncated octahedron is a 8-sided and space-filling shape.
Hexagonal prism is simulation space in the form of hexagonal prism.
Rectangular/cubic is a box-shaped simulation space, the most common and simple shape used for containing the molecular system.

A set of computational rules or procedures used to solve problems or perform tasks, including those in molecular simulations. Examples include integration algorithms for updating atomic positions and velocities.
A method used to control temperature in molecular dynamics simulations. It adjusts particle velocities to maintain a desired temperature, simulating a system's interaction with a heat bath.
Barostat is an algorithm used to control and maintain the pressure of a simulated system, typically work by adjusting the volume of the simulation box to maintain the desired pressure.

Berendsen barostat is a type of barostat algorithm that yields the correct target density, but it does not strictly sample from the isothermal-isobaric ensemble and typically yields volume fluctuations that are too low.
Monte Carlo barostat is a type of barostat algorithm that  samples rigorously from the isobaric-isothermal ensemble and does not necessitate computing the virial.

Andersen barostat is a type of barostat algorithm in which  the system is coupled to a pressure bath, and the coupling is achieved by including an additional degree of freedom in the equations of motion. This mathematical artifact mimics the action of a piston scaling the volume of the system.
Parrinello-Rahman is a type of barostat algorithm in which the system is couplet to a pressure bath, allowing to change the shape  and size of the box known as an anisotropic deformation of the box.

Langevin-piston barostat is based on Langevin thermostat with an additional damping (friction) force and stochastic force are introduced. Random collisions eliminate oscillation of the volume associated with the piston mass.
In Langevin thermostat, at each time step, all particles receive a random force and have their velocities lowered using a constant friction.
Berendsen thermostat samples canonical distribution by scaling all velocities to a random temperature probed from canonical distribution.

In the Andersen thermostat scheme, some prescribed number of particles is selected, and their momenta (actually, their velocities) are drawn from a Gaussian distribution at the prescribed temperature.
A specific thermostat algorithm used in molecular dynamics. It introduces an additional degree of freedom to the system to maintain constant temperature.

Constraining algorithm is a method used to maintain certain geometric properties of the simulated system, typically bond lengths or angles, at fixed values. It is used to remove high-frequency vibrations, allowing for larger time steps in simulations or maintain specific molecular geometries or structural features.

SHAKE is  type of constraining algorithm that  iteratively adjusting atomic positions to satisfy constraints after each unconstrained update. It uses Lagrange multipliers to enforce constraints and is typically applied to bonds involving hydrogen atoms.

RATTLE is the velocity version of SHAKE which is a popular algorithm for introducing distance constraints during molecular dynamics simulations. The RATTLE procedure is to go through the constraints one by one, adjusting the coordinates so as to satisfy each in turn.

LINCS is an algorithm that resets bonds to their correct lengths after an unconstrained update. The method is non-iterative, as it always uses two steps. Although LINCS is based on matrices, no matrix-matrix multiplications are needed.

Electrostatic interaction computing method is a method to handle electrostatic interactions. Electrostatic interaction is a long-range, attractive or repulsive forces between charged particles or molecules governed by Coulomb's law.

Particle Mesh Ewald Method is a method to handle electrostatic interaction by splitting the potential into short-range and long-range parts. The short-range part is calculated directly, while the long-range part is calculated using Fourier transforms on a grid.
Reaction Field (RF) is a method to simulate the effect of long-range dipole-dipole interactions when using periodic boundaries conditions.

Particle-Particle Particle-Mesh (P3M) is a method to compute electrostatic energy and forces, setting EPB in the output to zero and EEL that includes both the reaction field energy and the Coulombic energy.
Interaction type is the type of interaction described by the chemical  force-fields between two chemical entities.
Long-range interaction is the type of intereraction that take still place beyond of a specific distance cut-off (e.g. van der Waals, Hydrogen bond).
Short-range interaction is the type of interaction that take place under a specific distance cut-off (e.g. ionic, covalent, metallic, dipolar).
Specific interaction is the type of interaction described by the chemical  force-fields between two particular and defined chemical entities.
Non-specific interaction energy is the type of interaction described by the chemical  force-fields between two not defined chemical entities.

Non-covalent interactions is the type of interaction that differs from covalent bonds in that it does not involve the sharing of electrons, but rather involves more dispersed variations of electromagnetic interactions between molecules or within a molecule.

A covalent interaction, also known as a covalent bond, is a strong chemical bond that involves the sharing of electron pairs between atoms. In molecular dynamics simulations, covalent bonds are typically represented as rigid or semi-rigid connections between atoms, often modeled using harmonic potentials. These bonds are crucial for maintaining the primary structure of molecules like proteins and nucleic acids.
Type of interaction that take place between induced electrical forces between two or more atoms or molecules that are very close to each other.

Solvation model allows the quantum chemistry calculations to include the interactions between solvents and the quantum solute. Solvents can be treated implicitly, known as continuum solvents, and explicitly.
Explicit solvent model is solvent model that treat solvent molecules explicitly, including their coordinates and degrees of freedom.
A water model is used to simulate and thermodynamically calculate water clusters, liquid water, and aqueous solutions with explicit solvent.
Implicit solvent model is a solvent model treat the solvent as a continuous medium rather than individual molecules.
Hybrid solvent model is a solvent model that combine aspects of both explicit and implicit models.
Coarse Grained Solvent Model is a solvent model that simplify the representation of solvent molecules, often grouping multiple atoms into a single interaction site.
Machine learning solvent model is a solvent model based on machine-learning approaches.
Quantum Mechanical Solvent Model is a solvent model that is based on QM-calculations.
The Generalized Born (GB) model is an approximation method used in molecular dynamics simulations to efficiently model the electrostatic effects of solvent on biomolecules.
Similarity calculation metric is a metric that describe the level of similarity/dissimilarity necessary for two members to be in the same cluster.
Tanimoto Combo Score is a ROCS score that includes the shape score for similarity and the color score for similarity.

A molecular similarity measure that compares two molecular structures by calculating their overlap while allowing asymmetric weighting through parameters  and . The measure ranges from 0 (completely different) to 1 (identical), and can be adjusted to emphasize either the reference or query molecule in the comparison. It is particularly useful in molecular screening as it can identify both substructure and superstructure relationships between molecules.
Dice Coefficient metric emphasize the importance of shared features, often used in text mining and information retrieval.
Euclidean disteance sums the absolute differences of coordinates, also known as city block distance or L1 norm.
Manhattan distance measures the cosine of the angle between two vectors, often used in high-dimensional spaces.
Pearson correlation measures linear correlation between two sets of data, can be applied to various molecular properties.
Hamming distance counts the number of positions at which corresponding symbols in two strings are different, used for comparing binary fingerprints.
Jaccard index measures similarity between finite sample sets, similar to Tanimoto but for discrete data.
Overlap coefficient measures the overlap between two sets, useful when one set is a subset of the other.

A comprehensive molecular similarity measure that combines FitTversky shape matching with FitColorTversky chemical feature matching into a single metric. This measure emphasizes the database (fit) molecule's characteristics through its high  parameter value (0.95), making it particularly useful for identifying compounds where the query molecule is a substructure of database molecules. Like RefTverskyCombo, it produces scores typically ranging from 0 to 2, providing a balanced assessment of both geometric shape and chemical functionality similarities.

A specialized variant of the Tversky Index that uses fixed parameters with the alpha () value of  = 0.95, and beta () value of = 0.05 to heavily weight the reference molecule in the comparison. This asymmetric weighting makes it particularly effective at finding molecules that contain the reference structure as a substructure. RefTversky is commonly used in virtual screening to identify compounds that preserve key structural features of a reference molecule.
Combo score is a customizable combination of shape and color scores, allows users to define their own weighting scheme.

Optimal transformation path algorithm is an algorithm to find the most efficient way to transform one molecule into another in the context of free energy calculations, particularly in methods like thermodynamic integration or free energy perturbation.

Kruskal's algorithm finds a minimum spanning forest of an undirected edge-weighted graph. If the graph is connected, it finds a minimum spanning tree. It is a greedy algorithm that in each step adds to the forest the lowest-weight edge that will not form a cycle.

Prim's algorithm is a method for finding the minimum spanning tree (MST) of a weighted, undirected graph.  A minimum spanning tree is a subset of edges that connects all vertices with the minimum total edge weight.
Dijkstra's algorithm finds the shortest path between nodes in a graph, and can be adapted for finding optimal transformation paths.
A*search algorithm uses heuristics to find the optimal path more efficiently, can be applied to transformation path problems with appropriate heuristics.
Nearest-neighbor algorithm works by making a greedy approach that always chooses the closest unvisited node. This is simple but may not always find the optimal solution.
Genetic algorithms uses evolutionary principles to optimize the transformation path and can handle complex optimization problems but may be computationally intensive.
Simulated Annealing algorithm provides a probabilistic technique for approximating the global optimum. It can escape local minima in complex optimization landscapes.
Ant colony optimization algorithm is inspired by the behavior of ants finding paths, and can be adapted for finding optimal transformation paths in molecular systems.
Network flow algorithm can be used to find optimal paths in weighted graphs, such as Ford-Fulkerson and Edmonds-Karp algorithms.
A particular configuration or condition of a molecular system at a given time in a simulation. It includes atomic positions, velocities, and other relevant parameters.
A ligand state refers to a specific configuration or condition of a ligand molecule in the context of its interaction with a target protein or other biomolecules.

Bound ligand state is the configuration where the ligand is fully associated with the protein target, occupying a specific binding site. In this state, the ligand forms stable interactions (e.g., hydrogen bonds, van der Waals interactions) with the protein.

Unbound ligand state is the configuration where the ligand is completely separated from the protein, typically freely moving in the solvent. In this state, the ligand does not interact directly with the protein.

Transition ligand state is a high-energy, unstable configuration that represents the point of highest free energy along the reaction coordinate of ligand binding or unbinding. It's a fleeting state that determines the rate of binding/unbinding processes.

Metastable ligand state is a relatively stable intermediate configurations along the binding pathway that have local energy minima. These states can persist for some time before transitioning to other states.

Encounter complex ligand state is an initial, loosely bound complex formed when the ligand first comes into contact with the protein. This state often involves non-specific interactions and precedes the formation of the final, stable bound state.

Solvated ligand state is the configuration where the ligand is completely surrounded by solvent molecules (typically water) and fully hydrated. This state is important for understanding the energetics of desolvation during binding.

Conformational ligand state is different three-dimensional arrangements of the ligand's atoms that can interconvert. These can include folded vs. extended states, or different rotamers of flexible groups.

Protonation ligand state refers to the configuration of a ligand molecule based on the presence or absence of protons on specific atoms, particularly ionizable groups. It affects the ligand's charge distribution and binding properties, influencing its behavior in different pH environments and its interactions with target molecules. The protonation state can significantly affect the ligand's charge distribution and binding properties.

Tautomeric state is the state where structural isomers of the ligand are ready to interconvert, and differ in the position of a proton and a double bond. Tautomers can have different binding properties and may interconvert during the binding process.

Excited states are higher energy electronic configurations of a ligand where electrons occupy orbitals above the ground state. These states are crucial in photochemical processes and spectroscopic studies, representing temporary, energetically elevated molecular arrangements.
A systematic procedure for performing a molecular simulation or analysis. This can include specific algorithms, protocols, or techniques used to study molecular systems.
A technique used to analyze data from molecular simulations using statistical principles. These methods help extract meaningful information from large datasets generated by simulations.

Correlation Coefficient is numerical measure of some type of linear correlation between two variables. It ranges from -1 to +1, where 1 indicates the strongest possible correlation and 0 indicates no correlation.
Pearson's correlation coefficient (r) measures the linear correlation between predicted and experimental values. It ranges from -1 to 1, with 1 indicating perfect positive correlation.

Spearman's rank correlation coefficient assesses how well the predicted rankings of compounds match the experimental rankings. It is useful when the relative ordering of compounds is more important than absolute values.
Root-Mean-Square Deviation (RMSD) is a commonly used measure to quantify the difference between two sets of values, often used to compare structures or assess the accuracy of predictions.
Root Mean Square Fluctuation  (RMSF) measures the average deviation of a particle from its mean position. It is used to characterize local changes along the protein chain.
Bootstrapping is a resampling technique used to estimate confidence intervals and assess the robustness of results.
A statistical method for analyzing conformational dynamics in molecular simulations. MSMs represent the system as a network of states with transition probabilities between them.
Jensen-Shannon and Kullback-Leibler Divergences measure differences between probability distributions, useful for comparing conformational ensembles.

Kullback-Leibler divergence metric (relative entropy) is a statistical measurement from information theory that is commonly used to quantify the difference between one probability distribution from a reference probability distribution.
A method to simplify complex data from molecular simulations by reducing the number of variables. It helps in visualizing and analyzing high-dimensional data.
A specific dimensionality reduction technique often used in molecular simulation analysis. PCA identifies the main axes of variation in a dataset.
A method used to extract meaningful information from molecular simulation data. This can include statistical analysis, pattern recognition, or machine learning approaches.
Clustering analysis groups similar conformations to identify representative structures and analyze conformational diversity.
A procedure used to determine if a hypothesis about molecular simulation data is supported by evidence. It involves comparing observed data to expected outcomes under specific assumptions.
A specific statistical test used to compare distributions in molecular simulation data. It assesses whether two datasets differ significantly in their distribution.
Predictive Index (PI) measures the ability of the method to rank compounds by their binding affinity correctly. It is particularly useful in drug discovery applications.
Error metrics are statistical measures used to assess the accuracy, precision, and reliability of the computational predictions compared to experimental values.

Standard Error of the Mean (SEM), denoted as MSE, quantifies the precision of the estimated mean effective binding energy. A smaller SEM indicates a more precise estimate of the true mean. It is calculated by MSE = s / n where s is the sample standard deviation of the effective binding energies and n is the number of snapshots considered in the calculation.

RMSE measures the standard deviation of prediction errors, calculated as the square root of the average of squared differences between predicted and experimental values. It provides an overall measure of prediction accuracy.
MAE calculates the average of absolute differences between predicted and experimental values. It is less sensitive to outliers compared to RMSE.
MSE calculates the average of signed differences between predicted and experimental values. It is useful for detecting systematic bias in predictions.
A force field used in molecular dynamics simulations, particularly for biomolecules. It defines parameters for how atoms interact and is widely used for protein and lipid simulations.
Errors estimated by testing a model on data not used in its creation. This technique helps assess how well a model generalizes to new data.
BSE provides confidence intervals for the calculated binding energies. It is useful for assessing the robustness of the calculations.
Cross-Validation Errors assess the predictive performance and generalizability of the computational model.
Block Averaging estimates statistical inefficiency and provides error bars for correlated time series data. It is particularly useful for molecular dynamics simulations.
Hysteresis measures the difference between forward and backward transformations in alchemical free energy calculations. It indicates the extent of sampling problems.
Convergence Metrics assess whether the simulations have adequately sampled the relevant phase space, such as the Geweke diagnostic or auto-correlation time.
Measures used to quantify the similarity between different molecular conformations or states. These metrics help in understanding the conformational space sampled in simulations.
Predictive Index (PI) measures the ability of the method to correctly rank compounds by their binding affinity. It is particularly useful in drug discovery applications.
The criteria on how ligand pairs are selected.
Ligand pairs are selected based on structural similarity.
Ligand pairs are selected based on chemical similarity.
Ligand pairs are selected based on  the range of binding affinities to the target protein. Include both strong and weak binders to assess the method's ability to discriminate.
Ligand pairs are selected based on the diverse chemical structures and properties to cover a wide range of interactions. This include ligands with different functional groups, sizes, and shapes.

Ligand pairs are selected from ligands with reliable experimental binding data (e.g., Ki, IC50, or G values). This ensure the experimental data covers a sufficient dynamic range for statistical analysis.

Ligand pairs are selected from ligands with well-defined stereochemistry, tautomeric states, and protonation states. This include ligands within the domain of applicability of the computational method being used.
Ligand pairs are selected from pairs that represent specific structural changes, such as: a) Charge changes, b) Ring size modifications, c) Linker changes, and d) Binding mode alterations.
Ligand pairs are selected by considering the computational cost and selecting a manageable number of ligands.
Ligand pairs are selected from ligands that are representative of classical drug discovery targets and chemistries.
Ligand pairs are selected from ligands with high-quality protein-ligand complex structures (e.g., low B-factors, high resolution).
Ligand pairs are selected from ligands that are known to be stable in MD simulations.
Ligand pairs are selected based on ligand efficiency metrics to guide the selection and optimization of fragment hits in fragment-based drug discovery.
Software designed for a specific use. Examples include programs for structure visualization, trajectory analysis, or free energy calculations.
A framework is a reusable set of libraries, tools, and conventions for developing software applications.
Software utilities used to perform specific tasks in molecular simulations. These can range from file format converters to specialized analysis programs.
Short programs written to automate tasks in molecular simulations. They often combine multiple tools or programs to perform complex workflows.
Programs specifically designed to perform molecular dynamics simulations. These solve equations of motion for atoms over time, often using parallel computing techniques.
Quantum Mechanics Software is software tools used for quantum mechanics calculations in computational chemistry.
Software used to predict the orientation of molecules when they bind to each other. It's commonly used in drug discovery to predict how small molecules interact with protein targets.
Software used to create visual representations of molecular structures and simulation results. These tools help in understanding complex 3D structures and their dynamics.
Software used to examine and interpret data from molecular simulations. This can include programs for calculating various properties or identifying important events in simulations.
Software used to manipulate and transform data from molecular simulations. This includes programs for filtering, averaging, or reformatting simulation outputs.
Software used to change file formats in molecular simulation workflows. These tools are crucial for interoperability between different simulation and analysis programs.
A script used to automate repetitive tasks in molecular simulations. These scripts can manage entire simulation workflows, from system setup to analysis.
A script used to perform specific analyses on molecular simulation data. These often combine multiple analysis tools or implement custom calculations.
A script that outlines and executes a series of tasks in a molecular simulation project. It orchestrates the entire process from system preparation to final analysis.
Programs that can be run directly by a computer in molecular simulations. These are typically compiled from source code and optimized for performance.
Software that is operated through text commands in a console. Many molecular simulation tools are command-line programs, allowing for scripting and automation.
Software that has been converted from source code into machine code for execution. Compiled programs often run faster than interpreted scripts.
Quantum Mechanics-Molecular Mechanics-based method is a method to determine electronic structures and atoms-molecules connectivity.
A minimal basis set that approximates each Slater-type orbital with 2 Gaussian functions, providing the most basic representation of electronic structure at minimal computational cost. (UNVERIFIED)
Gaussian is a commercial software used to perform quantum chemistry calculations with various quantum chemical methods implementations.
GAMESS is a general ab initio quantum chemistry package.
Psi4 is an open-source suite of ab initio quantum chemistry programs designed for efficient, high-accuracy simulations of molecular properties.
ORCA is a powerful and versatile quantum chemistry software package, primarily developed by the group of Prof. Frank Neese.

A quantum chemistry software package that offers ab initio molecular dynamics and quasi-classical molecular dynamics simulations, particularly valuable for enzyme modeling, discovering reaction pathways, predicting protein-ligand binding energies, and modeling substrate binding to active sites. (UNVERIFIED)

An integrated suite of open-source computer codes for electronic-structure calculations and materials modeling that can perform structural optimization, find transition states, calculate minimum-energy pathways for chemical reactions, and conduct first-principle molecular dynamics simulations of biomolecular systems. (UNVERIFIED)

A computational chemistry software designed for scalability in handling large scientific problems across parallel computing resources, capable of simulating biomolecules, nanostructures, and solid-state systems using various methods from quantum to classical approaches, with support for ground and excited states calculations. (UNVERIFIED)
Molpro is a comprehensive system of ab initio programs for advanced molecular electronic structure calculations.
ChronusQ is a production quantum chemistry software package written in C++11 specializing in electronic dynamics and relativistic effects in molecular quantum mechanics.
QuTiP is open-source software for simulating the dynamics of open quantum systems.
interaction is a particular type of dispersion force from van der Waals forces, which is established between unsaturated (poly)cyclic molecules.
Hydrophobic interactions  is a type of non-covalent interaction that is the observed force of non-polar substances to aggregate in an aqueous solution and to be excluded by water.
Electrostatic interactions are forces between nearby atoms and molecules. Like charges will repel one another and opposite charges will attract.

Cation interaction is a non-covalent molecular interaction between the face of an electron-rich  system (e.g. benzene, ethylene, acetylene) and an adjacent cation (e.g. Li+, Na+). This interaction is an example of non-covalent bonding between a monopole (cation) and a quadrupole ( system).
Hydrogen bond is the interaction involving a hydrogen atom located between a pair of other atoms having a high affinity for electrons
Backbone hydrogen bonds are hydrogen bonds generated between backbone atoms in a polypeptidic chain.
Side chain hydrogen bonds are hydrogen bonds generated between side chain atoms in a polypeptidic chain.
Hydrogen bonds generated between side chain and backbone atoms in a polypeptidic chain.

A peptidic bond, also called a peptide bond, is a specific type of covalent bond that forms between the carboxyl group of one amino acid and the amino group of another amino acid. This bond is crucial in forming the primary structure of proteins. In molecular dynamics simulations, peptide bonds are usually treated as rigid planar units due to their partial double bond character.

Disulfide bridges are covalent bonds formed between the thiol groups (-SH) of two cysteine residues in proteins. These bonds play a crucial role in stabilizing protein tertiary and quaternary structures. In molecular dynamics simulations, disulfide bridges are usually modeled as covalent bonds, but their formation or breaking can be simulated in some advanced applications.
Ensemble is a statistical collection of possible states that a system can occupy under specific thermodynamic conditions.

Canonical ensemble or NVT ensemble  is a statistical ensemble that is used to study material properties under the conditions of a constant particle number N, constant volume V and a temperature fluctuating around an equilibrium value.

Isothermal-isobaric ensemble or NPT is a statistical ensemble that is used to study material properties under the conditions of a constant particle number N, constant pressure P and a temperature fluctuating around an equilibrium value.

Microcanonical ensemble or NVE is a statistical ensemble that is used to study material properties under the conditions of a constant particle number N, constant volume V and total energy fluctuating around an equilibrium value.
Grand canonical ensemble, or MuVT (VT), is an ensemble with a constant chemical potential (), volume (V), and temperature (T). In this ensemble, the system can exchange both energy and particles.
Techniques used to determine the three-dimensional structure of proteins. These include experimental methods like X-ray crystallography and computational methods like homology modeling.
A method used to determine the atomic and molecular structure of a crystal. It's widely used to solve protein structures by analyzing X-ray diffraction patterns.
A technique that uses magnetic properties of atomic nuclei to determine molecular structure. It's particularly useful for studying protein dynamics in solution.
A type of microscopy where samples are studied at cryogenic temperatures. It allows for high-resolution imaging of biomolecules in their native state.
Ligand charge model is a model or combination of QM-MM based models used for calculating the charges of specific molecular entities.
AM1BCC is a program that assigns atom types and bond types according to AM1-BCC definitions and then does bond charge correction.

Restrained Electrostatic Potential fitting approach is an established means for placing partial charges on atoms at the right intensities to mimic the electrostatic field outside of the molecular surface.
A script written for a specific purpose in a molecular simulation project. These often implement novel analysis methods or automate project-specific workflows.
The process of bringing a system to thermal equilibrium in a simulation. It involves gradually heating the system to the desired temperature.
The process of allowing a system to reach a stable state before data collection in a simulation. It ensures that the system's properties are no longer changing systematically.
A method used to calculate free energy differences along a reaction coordinate. It involves running multiple simulations with restraints to sample high-energy regions.
The main phase of a molecular dynamics simulation where data is collected. This phase follows system preparation and equilibration.
Methods used to compute free energy differences in molecular systems. These calculations are crucial for understanding molecular interactions and chemical processes.
A method that uses external forces to guide a system along a reaction coordinate. It adapts the applied force based on the system's response.

A minimal basis set that approximates each Slater-type orbital with 3 Gaussian functions, offering slightly improved accuracy over STO-2G while maintaining low computational requirements. (UNVERIFIED)
A minimal basis set that uses 4 Gaussian functions to approximate each Slater-type orbital, providing better orbital shapes than STO-3G but still considered minimal in accuracy. (UNVERIFIED)
The process of creating visual representations of molecular structures and simulation results. It helps in understanding complex 3D structures and their dynamics.
A suite of programs for molecular dynamics simulations. It's widely used for simulations of biomolecules, particularly proteins and nucleic acids.

AmberTools consists of several independently developed packages that work well by themselves, and with Amber24. The suite can also be used to carry out complete molecular dynamics simulations, with either explicit water or generalized Born solvent models.
A shell script used in Amber molecular dynamics workflows. It automates common tasks in Amber simulations.

Protonation tool is a tool  that prepares structures for further calculations by reconstructing missing atoms, adding hydrogens, assigning atomic charges and radii from specified force fields, and generating PQR files.

PDB2PQR is a software to prepare and optimize molecular structures prior to biomolecular simulations based on filling in missing parts, adding hydrogen, assigning charges and radii, and generate PQR files.
Ligand protonation software predicts the aqueous phase pKa values and protonation state distributions of complex, drug-like molecules.
A tool used to assign protonation states to molecules in simulations. It's crucial for accurately representing the chemical state of molecules at a given pH.
Epik is a tool for accurately and rapidly predicting the aqueous phase pKa values and protonation state distributions of complex, drug-like molecules.
Membrane packing software builds membrane-proteinlipid-bilayer systems.
PACKMOL-Memgen is a software to create virtual models of cell membranes with proteins embedded in the cell membranes.
Membrane protein orienting tool is used for orienting membrane proteins prior to performing molecular dynamics simulations.
memembed is a software to determine the membrane proteins orientation inside cell membranes/lipid bilayers.
Simulation type is the type of molecular dynamics simulation being conducted.

All-Atom molecular dynamics is a computational simulation technique that models the behavior and interactions of all atoms in a molecular system over time by solving Newton's equations of motion. All-atoms MD uses empirical force fields or inter-atomic potentials to calculate the forces between atoms and their potential energies.
Different forms of energy considered in molecular simulations. These can include bonded interactions (like bond stretching) and non-bonded interactions (like electrostatics).
Bond energy is a measure of the strength of a chemical bond.
Gravitational interaction energy is an attraction, the force of interaction being proportional to the product of the masses of the chemical entities.
Electromagnetic interaction energy is an interaction energy that exists between electrically charged particles and bodies through an electromagnetic field.
Nuclear interaction energy is the minimum energy that is required to disassemble the nucleus of an atom into its constituent protons and neutrons.
A technique for combining data from multiple simulations. It's often used to calculate free energy profiles from umbrella sampling simulations.

PMF Method is a computational technique used in molecular dynamics simulations to calculate free energy profiles along a reaction coordinate. PMF provides the free energy profile along a chosen reaction coordinate, allowing researchers to understand the energetics of processes like protein folding, ligand binding, or ion transport, and typically use Umbrella Sampling.

Trajectory approach describe how MD trajectories are generated and utilized to calculate binding free energies in methods like MM-PBSA or MM-GBSA. The approach determines which molecular systems are simulated and how the data from these simulations is used in the calculations.

Single trajectory approach in molecular dynamics simulations refers to a method where only one simulation of the complex (e.g. protein-ligand bound state) is performed, rather than separate simulations of the complex, protein, and ligand.
pKa Tool  is a tool that predicts the pKa values of ionizable groups in protein at the specified pH.

PROPKA is  a software to predict the pKa values of ionizable groups in protein and protein ligands complexes; enable the understanding of the behavior of proteins or other biological molecules in different environments.
A Python script for performing MMPBSA calculations in Amber. It automates the process of calculating binding free energies from molecular dynamics trajectories.
The software used for performing in-silico mutagenesis of target proteins of interest. Different softwares are available on the market to fulfill this task.
FoldX evaluates in-silico mutants by evaluating the difference in protein folding free energy between wild-type and a mutant of interest.
The tunnel predictor tool allows the identification of surface-exposed as well as hidden tunnels across MD simulation ensembles.
CAVER is a software tool for analysis and visualization of tunnels and channels in protein structures.
A molecular dynamics package primarily designed for bio-molecular systems. It's known for its high performance and is widely used in the scientific community.

A versatile molecular simulation program (Chemistry at HARvard Molecular Mechanics) focused on biological molecules such as proteins, peptides, lipids, nucleic acids, and carbohydrates, providing a comprehensive suite of computational tools for conformational sampling, free energy estimation, molecular minimization, and dynamics analysis. (UNVERIFIED)
Parameters used to describe the behavior of ions in molecular simulations. These include charge, size, and interaction energies with other atoms.
A specific set of ion parameters used in molecular simulations. It's designed to accurately represent the behavior of metal ions in bio-molecular systems.
Tool used for trajectory post-processing and analysis.
CPPTRAJ is the main program in Amber for processing coordinate trajectories and data files.
A method used to group similar molecular conformations. It helps in identifying dominant structures or states in a simulation trajectory.
In data mining and statistics, hierarchical clustering is a method of cluster analysis that seeks to build a hierarchy of clusters.
Methods to predict interactions between molecules without dynamics. These often use simplified models to quickly estimate binding affinities.
The process of predicting the preferred orientation of a ligand when bound to a protein. It's widely used in drug discovery to screen potential drug candidates.
Programs that use classical mechanics to model molecular systems. They treat atoms as spheres and bonds as springs, ignoring quantum effects.
Antechamber is a set of auxiliary programs for molecular mechanic (MM) studies.
Software used to create initial structures for molecular simulations. It defines the connectivity of atoms and their initial positions.

tleap is used to prepare molecular systems for simulation, including generating topology and coordinate files needed to run molecular dynamics. definition.val: MMPBSA (Molecular Mechanics Poisson-Boltzmann Surface Area) is a computational method for calculating binding free energies between molecules, such as protein-ligand or protein-protein interactions. nodes.lbl: molecular mechanics generalized Born surface area

A negative G indicates that the second ligand binds more strongly than the first.

Electrostatic Energy Contribution refers to the energy arising from Coulombic interactions between charged particles, calculated using Coulomb's law, and is the sum of all pairwise interactions in a system. This energy, which can be attractive or repulsive, plays a crucial role in the structure and behavior of biomolecules and is often calculated using methods like Particle Mesh Ewald in molecular dynamics simulations.

Van der Waals Energy Contribution arises from temporary fluctuations in electron distribution, including dispersion, induction, and orientation forces, and is generally attractive at longer distances but repulsive at very short distances. Though weaker than electrostatic interactions, it is significant when summed over many atoms and is crucial for phenomena like protein folding and material properties, often modeled using the Lennard-Jones potential in simulations.

The error in Gibbs free energy change (G) represents the uncertainty in the calculated or measured G for processes like ligand binding, quantifying the precision of these measurements and typically reported in kcal/mol or kJ/mol. It arises from various sources such as experimental and statistical errors, and understanding G is crucial for the reliability of free energy calculations, especially in drug discovery, where the difference in G should exceed the combined errors for meaningful comparisons.

Cutoff is a point serving as the limit beyond which something is no longer possible.
Energy cutoff signifies the energy beyond which the system is ignored or treated differently.
Velocity cutoff is the velocity beyond which the system is ignored or treated differently.
Distance cutoff is the distance beyond which non-bonded interactions (like van der Waals and electrostatic interactions) between atoms are ignored or treated differently.
A method to limit the movement of specific atoms using a spring-like force. It's often used to maintain certain structural features during simulations.

definition.val: This boolean property signifies whether entropy component calculated as part of the MM-PBSA (Molecular Mechanics Poisson-Boltzmann Surface Area) method for estimating binding free energies. It aims to account for the change in entropy upon binding between a ligand and receptor.

Indicates whether Adaptive Steered Molecular Dynamics (ASMD) is involved. ASMD is an enhanced sampling technique that builds upon traditional Steered Molecular Dynamics (SMD). ASMD divides the reaction coordinate into multiple segments or stages. Within each stage, multiple SMD simulations are performed.
Grid function is the function used  in CPPTRAJ for the density maps calculations.

The properties of CPPTRAJ settings. CPPTRAJ is a program for processing and analyzing molecular dynamics trajectory data. It's part of the Amber software suite and can perform various analyses on simulation outputs.
The computational setup and conditions under which a molecular simulation is run. This may include hardware specifications, operating systems, or parallel processing setups.
Indicates whether a simulation involves a molecule spanning a lipid membrane. It's relevant for studying membrane proteins or cellular processes at membranes.

A parameter representing the dielectric properties inside a molecule (typically a protein or ligand) during MMPBSA calculations. It reflects how the molecule's internal environment responds to electric fields and affects the calculation of electrostatic interactions.

A parameter representing the dielectric properties of the environment surrounding the molecule (typically the solvent) during MMPBSA calculations. It characterizes how the surrounding medium responds to electric fields and is usually set to approximate water's dielectric properties (around 80).
